Why doesn't the Fed do its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new board members of the US central bank Federal Reserve gives people in America – and the US Congress – an opportunity to think about the world's most important central bank and its future direction.
The obvious, first question to be asked is how it was possible for the Fed to fail so miserably in fulfilling its most important mandate - ensuring price stability.
That the Fed was completely caught off guard by the current inflation suggests a fundamental failure.
Clearly, institutional soul-searching is in order.
While monetary policy makes headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
Another major question is therefore whether it will use its immense power to drive climate or social policy forward.
The Fed could, for example, deny loans to companies in the fossil fuel sector, it could require banks to only grant loans to companies with certified net-zero emission plans, or steer credit towards the desired alternatives.
In addition, it could decide to take its regulatory activity explicitly on behalf of equality or ethnic justice by instructing banks on where and to whom to grant loans, who to hire and who to fire, and so on.
Before we turn to the question of which direction the Fed's regulation will or should move, we must first clarify the Fed's grave failure.
In 2008, the US government made a fateful decision: while financial institutions could still largely secure funds for risky investments by selling short-term, risk-prone debt instruments, hordes of new regulatory agencies would henceforth evaluate the risk profile of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that regulatory bodies would no longer overlook large chunks in the magnitude of subprime mortgages on bank balance sheets.
In the ensuing ten years of more detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's regulatory army has never once asked itself what actually happens in the event of a pandemic.
As the pandemic actually occurred in early 2020, the Fed jettisoned its "never again" pledges from 2008 and intervened on an even greater scale.
In March, commercial banks proved unable to function as intermediaries on the market for vanilla US government bonds.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. Corrections on the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms were put off until later.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed bailed out the money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs in the money market, but it never came to that.
Therefore, the Fed also funded the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially providing a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes".
In 2008, the Fed and the US Treasury had initially opposed the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the financial sector bailout package, the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
However, in 2020, the so-called "Powell put" - among other things - had introduced an explicit floor for corporate bond prices.
So what?
The lockdowns due to COVID-19 could have certainly triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks because the Fed and the US Treasury will simply put out every new fire with a new flood of money.
The incentives created by these strategies are the problem.
What's the point of going to the trouble of using reserve funds or balance sheet capacity for purchases at falling prices, to provide liquidity or treat a forced sale as a buying opportunity?
The Fed will inevitably outdo them and reap the profits.
Why would companies still issue stocks when they can simply take out a loan, knowing that the state will back the debt or bail them out, as was the case with airlines?
Why would investors hesitate when it comes to buying dubious papers if their value in bad times is guaranteed by another "whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed?
It's no wonder that America is drowning in debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will foot the bill for the next downturn.
Student loans, government pensions, and mortgages are piling up and waiting for Uncle Sam's rescue operation to take over.
However, every new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Investors will eventually refuse to put more money into rescue operations, and people will not be pleased with billions of newly printed money.
If the expected rescue packages do not materialize, we will wake up to a major blaze – and the fire station will have been reduced to ashes.
In 2008, at least regulatory bodies and lawmakers recognized the moral risk and were concerned that in good times investors would reap profits while in bad times taxpayers would bear the losses.
In 2020, one only indulged in complacency with the rescue operations.
The Fed, which failed to anticipate the risks of subprime mortgages in 2008 just as it did the 2020 pandemic, and is now conducting stress tests to address "climate risks," will undoubtedly also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next sovereign default, or another disruptive event.
The regulators at the Fed do not even pose the question about the mentioned events.
And although dictionaries are produced over "interconnections," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles," it has not been possible to define the "systemic" risk at all, except that it has become a catch-all term that confers all-encompassing power on regulatory bodies.
Regulatory bodies will never be able to anticipate risks, accurately measure the assets of financial institutions, or ensure that immense debts are always paid.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system in which the state always stands ready to bail out debt mountains in times of crisis. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
A more effective regulation can bridge partisan divides.
The Left is right when it claims that the large banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit most Americans very little.
However, it is based on the wrong cause.
A tremendous effort to comply with regulations is a significant barrier to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is futile.
Regulatory provisions are either wise or foolish, effective or ineffective, full of unwanted consequences or well-conceived.
We need more effective regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and does not require regulatory bodies to possess prophetic abilities.
The Fed scandalously halted companies in the Narrow Banking and payment services sector, which could have contributed to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before devoting itself to saving the planet and making amends for injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how inadequately it fulfills its fundamental duty of protecting the financial system.
